Wash and dry all produce. Adjust oven rack to upper position and preheat #oven{} to 450 degrees. Halve, peel, and dice @yellow onion{1}(peeled and diced). Trim, then thinly slice @scallions{2}(sliced, greens and whites separated). Halve, core, and seed @poblano pepper{1}(halved, cored, and seeded), then cut into ½-inch pieces. Pat @chicken breast strips{10%oz} dry with a #paper towel{}.

Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%tsp} in a large #pan{} over medium-high heat. Add @salt{} and @pepper{}, onion and poblano and cook, tossing, until slightly softened, about ~{2%minutes}.

Add chicken and half the @southwest spice blend{1%tbsp} to same pan. Cook, tossing occasionally, until chicken is browned and cooked through, ~{4-5%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper. Remove pan from heat and set aside.

Heat a drizzle of oil and @butter{1%tbsp} in another, medium-sized pan over medium-high heat. Add scallion whites, @enchilada spice blend{1%tbsp}, and remaining southwest spice. Cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}. Add @tomato paste{6%tbsp} and cook ~{1-2%minutes}, stirring constantly. Stir in @water{1%cup} and @sugar{½%tsp}. Bring to a simmer and let thicken slightly, about ~{2%minutes}. Season with plenty of salt and pepper. Remove pan from heat.

Place a @flour tortillas{2} on your work surface and add half the chicken mixture towards one side. Roll up tortilla and place seam-side down in a #small baking dish{} or #ovenproof pan{}. Repeat with remaining tortilla and chicken mixture, placing rolls side-by-side. Spoon over enough sauce to generously coat (you may not need all). Sprinkle evenly with @Mexican cheese blend{½%cup}.

Place #baking dish{} in oven and bake until sauce is bubbly and cheese melts, about ~{2%minutes}. Dollop baked enchiladas with @sour cream{4%tbsp}. Sprinkle with scallion greens. Divide between plates and spoon over any remaining sauce.

> In case you'd like a refresher on what enchiladas are, they're stuffed and rolled tortillas baked casserole style with a generous amount of sauce. You could think of them as sauce-drenched burritos that you eat with a knife and fork. In other words, pure awesomeness, right? Of course, although it only gets better when you factor in the chicken strips, Southwest spices, shredded cheese, and sour cream that comes with this version.